 medical equipment company however the investigation by the ndrc into medtronic’s violations only began in  allowing for the possibility that abuses had continued for more than eight years in total in medtronic’s case the percent figure comes out to  billion yuan for the  fiscal year — much more than the company’s total fine a better response would be to confiscate illegal gains or to model the law on countries in the european union that set the maximum fine at  percent of a company’s global profits a closer look at the fine print also reveals that the ndrc did not investigate all of medtronic’s business in mainland china again because of its narrow definition of “income” instead it only accounted for around  billion yuan of the company’s total  billion yuan in sales revenue in exchange the ndrc exacted an antimonopoly fine of only  million yuan and did not pursue the investigation in other provinces similarly the medtronic case raises several questions did the ndrc use the “mercedes model” to secure medtronic’s cooperation with the antimonopoly investigation state broadcaster cctv reported that the antimonopoly investigation team had to place more than  international calls to the company’s us like mercedesbenz the company withdrew its rebuttal of the antimonopoly enforcement organizations this allows lawbreakers to continue engaging in illegal activity knowing that the maximum fine will never exceed their existing illegal gains second china’s antimonopoly law stipulates that the fine for refusing to cooperate stalling or wasting enforcement resources during the antimonopoly investigation is capped at only  million yuan this significantly lowers the base fine imposed on the company this autonomy prevails regardless of the duration of illegal activity or the extent of its damage the case clearly shows that the extensive discretion enjoyed by enforcement agencies has been coopted by lawbreakers to exploit china’s antimonopoly regulations and give lobbyists more room to pressure the law enforcement agencies a working draft of a policy document aimed at tightening fining procedures was released in june  but it was condemned for lacking detail finally the courts should protect the right of consumers affected by companies that flout antimonopoly laws to sue those companies for compensation header image the national flag of china flutters behind a fence of the headquarters of the national development and reform commission ndrc in beijing july  the long in medtronic’s case the percent figure comes out to  billion yuan for the  fiscal year — much more than the company’s total fine state broadcaster cctv reported that the antimonopoly investigation team had to place more than  international calls to the company’s us second china’s antimonopoly law stipulates that the fine for refusing to cooperate stalling or wasting enforcement resources during the antimonopoly investigation is capped at only  million yuan the case clearly shows that the extensive discretion enjoyed by enforcement agencies has been coopted by lawbreakers to exploit china’s antimonopoly regulations and give lobbyists more room to pressure the law enforcement agencies finally the courts should protect the right of consumers affected by companies that flout antimonopoly laws to sue those companies for compensationfirst we have the insulin bottlehere is the syringe i use to draw the insulin from the vialbubbles frequently appear so i have to use a pen to whack them to the topheres the full package for the minimed  insertertaking the cap off to open the inserter upmedtroniccompanyread more from httpwwwmedtroniccomusenindexhtmlmedtronic is a medical device company headquartered in dublin ireland their operational headquarters is in fridley minnesota medtronic is the worlds largest standalone medical technology development company read more from httpsenwikipediaorgwikimedtronicfirst we have the insulin bottlehere is the syringe i use to draw the insulin from the vialbubbles f